snippet.textDisplay:
STORYTIME : I was traumatised by chickens hatching.
So, when I was in primary school, the science classroom had this incubator to hatch chickens. I loved it. Every spring, they got like a dozen chicken eggs and chucked ‘em in there. It was great, they always hatched, I got to witness it a lot, 12 outa 10, would recommend. And then, one quite nice day in Year Six, the last year of Primary School (so, I was on the younger side, I was a new ten year old who thought they had the world), a big crack appeared in one of the eggs. No eggs had hatched yet, so this was a big deal. We spent most of the lesson going back to being horribly traumatised by animations to show us how babies are made (which, I was ten, Mrs Wild what were you thinking?). Then, in the last five minutes, another crack appeared in another one of the eggs. We scrammed over there, and discovered that the first egg was shaking violently. We made a big semi-circle around it, watching and hoping that we’d witness two eggs hatching.
We did.
The first egg hatched first. Mrs Wild told us that it was unlikely that the second egg would hatch. She was wrong. It did hatch, and this traumatised me even more than the sex Ed animations (once again, I WAS TEN, MRS WILD WHAT IS WRONG WITH YOU). So, the second chicken, who I shall call Bob, was laying dramatically on the floor, exhausted. The first chicken was up and moving, and this vicious little [insert family friendly word here because I can’t think of any below PG 15], who we shall call Martha, comes over to Bob. AND THIS TINY BEBE CHICKEN PECKS BOB IN THE EYEBALL. I REPEAT: THIS NEWLY HATCHED CHICKEN PECKS BOB, HER BEBE BROTHER, IN THE EYEBALL.
Oh, fun fact, Bob never opened that eye again. It stayed closed for as long as I knew him.
